cs.IT, cs.SP, cs.NA, cs.SI, cs.MM. 

The paper discusses random matrices that appear in communication and signal processing applications, which suggests that it could belong to cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.SP (Signal Processing). The focus on the reconstruction error of an irregularly sampled bandlimited signal further supports the possibility of cs.SP. The use of quasi-equally spaced vectors and the derivation of distribution moments suggest a numerical analysis approach, which could place the paper in cs.NA (Numerical Analysis). The paper could also be relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) if the irregular sampling is related to network data. Finally, the mention of matrix size and aspect ratio could indicate a connection to cs.MM (Multimedia).
